---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="About | Group Scout" description="Who's behind groupscout and why it exists">
  <div class="max-w-2xl mx-auto py-8">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-zinc-900 dark:text-zinc-100 mb-8">About</h1>

    <div class="prose prose-zinc dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        Hi, I'm Alvin — a software developer based in BC. This project started by watching my
        wife, a hotel sales manager near YVR, do her job and thinking:
        <em>there has to be a better way to find these leads.</em>
      </p>

      <p>
        Hotel group sales is a particular kind of grind. You're not waiting for the phone to ring —
        you're expected to go find the business. Construction crews housing dozens of workers for
        months. Sports teams traveling for tournaments. Film productions booking large room blocks
        on tight timelines. The goal is simple: find them before your competitor does.
      </p>

      <p>
        The signals exist, but they're scattered. Building permits here. Contract awards there.
        A relevant news story buried in a Google Alert. Manually connecting the dots is slow,
        inconsistent, and easy to miss.
      </p>

      <p>
        So I'm building
        <a href="https://github.com/alvindcastro/groupscout">Group Scout</a> —
        a Go-based backend that monitors public data for these signals and uses LLM-assisted
        enrichment to prioritize potential group sales opportunities. No dashboards. No logins.
        Just a focused list of leads and the context behind them.
      </p>

      <p>
        This blog documents the process: technical decisions, false starts, the
        <q>wait, how does hotel sales actually work?</q> moments, and (hopefully) the wins.
        It doubles as a learning exercise — both for me, and for anyone interested in using
        software to solve real-world problems that aren't glamorous but matter.
      </p>

      <p>
        The hotel is real. The problem is real. Let's see if the solution works.
      </p>


      <p>
        For work history and experience, see my
        <a
            href="/AlvinDeCastro.pdf"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
        >
          resume (PDF)
        </a>.
      </p>

    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
